# Given a filename, return the filepath. Default folder is the `data` folder in the current working directory.
get_path <- function(filename) {
  str_c(getwd(), "data", filename, sep = "/")
}

# Colors:
ISLR_blue <- "#176FC0"
ISLR_brown <- "#94340E"
ISLR_lightblue <- "#68A5DB"
ISLR_orange <- "#CC5318"

# Return vector of the names of numeric columns in a data frame:
numeric_cols <- function(df) {
  is_numeric_cols <- map_lgl(df, is.numeric)
  return(names(df)[is_numeric_cols])
}

# predict() function for regsubsets() as given in the book:
predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id,...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id=id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

# Print accuracy, test rate and table of predicted labels and true labels:
test_rates <- function(predicted_label, test_label) {
  print(table(predicted_label, test_label))
  test_accuracy <- mean(predicted_label == test_label)*100
  test_error <- mean(predicted_label != test_label)*100
  print(str_interp("Test accuracy: ${round(test_accuracy, 2)}"))
  print(str_interp("Test error rate: ${round(test_error, 2)}"))
}

# Plot histograms and return a list of them:
plot_histogram <- function(df, var) {
  g <- ggplot(data = df, aes(x = .data[[var]])) + # Ref for passing var names to functions for plots: https://stackoverflow.com/a/55524126
    geom_histogram(bins = 30,
                   color = "white")
  return(g)
}

# Plot boxplots and return a list of them:
plot_boxplot <- function(df, var1, var2) {
  g <- ggplot(data = df, aes(x = .data[[var1]], y = .data[[var2]])) +
     geom_boxplot() 
  return(g)
}

# Linear regression diagnostic plots:
plot_lm_diagnostics <- function(model) {
  lindia::plot_all(
    plots = list(
      gg_resfitted(model), 
      gg_qqplot(model),
      gg_scalelocation(model),
      gg_resleverage(model)
    )
  )
}

Exercise 6

View data:

Wage

(a)

Perform polynomial regression to predict wage using age. Use cross-validation to select the optimal degree \(d\) for the polynomial.

### Train/Test
set.seed(1)
n <- nrow(Wage)
d.max <- 5 # max degree of polynomial
train <- sample(n, 4*n/5) # 80%/20% train/test
test <- (-train)

### CV
k = 10
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(Wage[train, ]), replace=TRUE)
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, d.max, dimnames=list(NULL, paste(1:d.max)))

Training

Perform CV on the training data to select the optimum value of \(d\) for polynomial regression:

for(j in 1:k) {
  for(i in 1:d.max) {
    fit <- lm(wage ~ poly(age, i), data = Wage[train, ][folds!=j, ])
    pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Wage[train, ][folds==j, ])
    cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((pred - Wage$wage[train][folds==j])^2)
  }
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)
d.min <- which.min(mean.cv.errors)
sort(mean.cv.errors)
       4        5        3        2        1 
1501.181 1501.978 1503.196 1507.334 1582.349

Plot the CV errors for each \(d\):

data.frame(d = 1:d.max, error = mean.cv.errors) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(d, error)) +
  geom_line(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(data = data.frame(x = which.min(mean.cv.errors), y = mean.cv.errors[which.min(mean.cv.errors)]),
             aes(x, y), color = ISLR_orange, size = 2) +
  labs(y = "Mean CV Error", title = "Mean CV Error for polynomial regressions of degree d")

Cross validation on the training set has chosen 5 degrees as optimal.

Test Error

Fit a model using the optimum \(d\), then calculate the error on the test data:

fit <- lm(wage ~ poly(age, d.min), data = Wage[train, ])
pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Wage[test, ])
mse <- mean((pred - Wage$wage[test])^2)
mse

Calculate the R-squared value:

R_sq <- 1 - mse / mean((mean(Wage$wage[test]) - Wage$wage[test])^2)

(b)

Fit a step function to predict wage using age, and perform cross-validation to choose the optimal number of cuts, \(c\).

Training

Perform CV on the training data to select the optimum value of \(c\):

set.seed(1)
c.max <- 15 # max number of cuts
age.min = min(Wage$age) - 0.1 # Take away 0.1 for cut()
age.max = max(Wage$age) + 0.1 # Add 0.1 for cut()
k <- 10 # small k is required to avoid error
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(Wage[train, ]), replace=TRUE)
cv.errors <- matrix(NA, k, c.max, dimnames=list(NULL, paste(1:c.max)))
for(j in 1:k) {
  for(i in 2:c.max) {
    breaks <- seq(age.min, age.max, length.out = i + 1) # see note [1]
    fit <- lm(wage ~ cut(age, breaks), data = Wage[train, ][folds!=j, ])
    pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Wage[train, ][folds==j, ])
    cv.errors[j, i] <- mean((pred - Wage$wage[train][folds==j])^2)
  }
}

# [1] The breaks are calculated explicitly so that the same breaks are used for all folds. If the cut() function is allowed to automatically choose the breaks ( ie `cut(age, i)` ), then errors will arise as different folds will have different breaks.

mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)
c.min <- which.min(mean.cv.errors)
sort(mean.cv.errors)
      11        8       12       13       15       10        7       14        9        6        5        4        3        2 
1505.999 1508.259 1508.821 1511.219 1512.516 1514.504 1516.421 1517.186 1519.339 1524.481 1535.584 1542.932 1587.657 1637.830

Plot the CV errors for each \(c\):

data.frame(c = 1:c.max, error = mean.cv.errors) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(c, error)) +
  geom_line(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(data = data.frame(x = which.min(mean.cv.errors), y = mean.cv.errors[which.min(mean.cv.errors)]),
             aes(x, y), color = ISLR_orange, size = 2) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:c.max) +
  labs(y = "Mean CV Error", title = "Mean CV Error for step functions with c cuts")

Cross validation on the training set has chosen 11 cuts as optimal.

Variable Selection:

Variable selection and regression (see separate notebook caller chap7_q7_regression.Rmd) chose a lasso regression as the best fit. Fit a polynomial regression model using polynomial transformations of year and age, combined with the maritl and race variables which were included in the lasso model:

### Data:
data <- Wage # `data` is the full data set
y.index = 11 # column index of response variable

X <- data[ , -c(y.index, 6)]
y <- data[, y.index]
n = nrow(X)
p = ncol(X)
var.names <- names(X)
df <- data.frame(X, y) # data.frame for use in modeling

### Train/Test
set.seed(1)
n <- nrow(Wage)
d.max <- 5 # max degree of polynomial
train <- sample(n, 4*n/5) # 80%/20% train/test
test <- (-train)

### CV
k = 10 # no. of folds
d.max <- 5
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(Wage[train, ]), replace=TRUE)
cv.errors <- array(NA, c(k, d.max, d.max), dimnames=list(NULL, paste("d_1:", 1:d.max), paste("d_2:", 1:d.max)))

Training

Perform cross validation on the training data to select the optimum value of \(d\) for polynomial regression:

for(j in 1:k) {
  for(d_1 in 1:d.max) { # d_1 : year
    for(d_2 in 1:d.max) { # d_2 : age
      fit <- lm(wage ~ poly(year, d_1) + poly(age, d_2) + maritl + race, data = Wage[train, ][folds!=j, ])
      pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Wage[train, ][folds==j, ])
      cv.errors[j, d_1, d_2] <- mean((pred - Wage$wage[train][folds==j])^2)
    }
  }
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, c(2, 3), mean)
d.min <- arrayInd(which.min(mean.cv.errors), dim(mean.cv.errors))
d.min # the first number is the polynomial degree for year, the second is age
     [,1] [,2]
[1,]    3    4

Test Error

Fit a model on all of the training data using the optimum values for \(d\), then calculate the error on the test data:

fit <- lm(wage ~ poly(year, d.min[1]) + poly(age, d.min[2]) + maritl + race, data = Wage[train, ])
pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Wage[test, ])
mse <- mean((pred - Wage$wage[test])^2) # MSE
mse
[1] 1920.766

Calculate the R-squared value:

R_sq <- 1 - mse / mean((mean(Wage$wage[test]) - Wage$wage[test])^2)
R_sq

The lasso model in the chap7_q7_regression.Rmd notebook returned a test error of 1061.490 and R-squared of 0.3293014, which is considerably better than this polynomial models performance.

From the pairs() plot it is apparent that there is a non-linear relationship between mpg and displacement, horsepower, weight, and possibly acceleration.

Use cross validation to generate a polynomial regression model (keep acceleration as a linear variable for now):

for(j in 1:k) {
  for(d_1 in 1:d.max) { # d_1 : displacement
    for(d_2 in 1:d.max) { # d_2 : horsepower
      for(d_3 in 1:d.max) { # d_3 : weight
        fit <- lm(mpg ~
                    poly(displacement, d_1) +
                    poly(horsepower, d_2) +
                    poly(weight, d_3) +
                    acceleration + year + cylinders + origin,
                  data = Auto[train, ][folds !=j, ]
        )
        pred <- predict(fit, newdata = Auto[train, ][folds==j, ])
        cv.errors[j, d_1, d_2, d_3] <- mean((pred - Auto$mpg[train][folds==j])^2)
      }
    }
  }
}

Find the optimum values of \(d\):

mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, c(2, 3, 4), mean)

predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id,...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id=id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

Forward Stepwise Selection

Use forward stepwise selection and cross-validation (on the training set only) to select a model:

for(j in 1:k) {
  forward.fit <- regsubsets(y ~ ., data=df[train, ][folds!=j, ], nvmax=r.max, method = "forward")
  for(i in 1:r.max) {
    pred <- predict.regsubsets(forward.fit, df[train, ][folds==j, ], id=i)
    cv.errors[j, i] = mean((pred - y[train][folds==j])^2)
  }
}

Exercise 12

(a)

start <- bh_start_timer()
[1] "Start time: 2021-04-15 16:42:54"
set.seed(2)
n <- 100 # no. of observations
p <- 10 # no. of predictors (p < n)
X <- matrix(NA, nrow = n, ncol = p + 1) # (p + 1) for beta0
X[ , 1] <- rep(1, n) # column of 1's for beta0

# Randomly initialize X:
for(i in 2:(p+1)) {
  mean <- sample(-10:10, 1)
  sd <- sample(1:5, 1)
  X[ , i] <- rnorm(n, mean, sd) 
}

# Randomly initialize beta:
# beta <- seq(-100, 100, length = 500) %>%
#           sample(p + 1, replace = TRUE)
beta <- seq(-5, 5, length = 500) %>%
          sample(p + 1, replace = TRUE)

# y = beta * X:
y <- mapply("*", as.data.frame(X), beta) %>% 
     apply(1, sum)

K <- 500 # max no. of iterations for backfitting

# Estimated beta:
beta.hat <- matrix(NA, nrow = K, ncol = p + 1) # (p + 1) for beta 0
beta.hat[1, ] <- rep(1, p + 1) # initialize all beta estimates to 1

# Backfitting: use a loop to update the estimates (K-1) more times:
for(k in 2:K) {
  if(k %% 25 == 0) { # check for convergence every 25 iterations
    print(str_c("k: ", k, "..."))
    if(sum(abs(apply(beta.hat[(k-6):(k-2), ], 2, mean) - beta.hat[k-1, ])) / p < 1e-02) {  
      break # convergence when last five rows show no change
    }
  }
  for(i in 1:(p+1)) {
    ### Hold all but one beta.hat fixed and update it:
    a <- y - (mapply("*", as.data.frame(X[ , -i]), beta.hat[k-1, -i]) %>% apply(1, sum))
    if(i != 1) {
      beta.hat[k, i] <- lm(a ~ X[ , i], data = data.frame(X[ , i], y))$coef[2]
    } else {
      beta.hat[k, i] <- lm(a ~ X[ , i], data = data.frame(X[ , i], y))$coef[1] # beta0
    }
  }
}
[1] "k: 25..."
end <- bh_end_timer()
[1] "End time: 2021-04-15 16:42:55"
bh_run_time(start, end)
[1] "Run time: 1.93 secs"
# Plot the values for beta up until the value of k when convergence occurred:
p1 <- cbind(data.frame(k = 1:(k-1)), beta.hat[1:(k-1) ,-1]) %>% # k-1 because it stops at the kth iteration leaving NA's 
  pivot_longer(!contains("k"), names_to = "beta", values_to = "estimate") %>%
